        {
            "text": "into cDNA using 1 L (10 M) of reverse primer in a 20 L reaction volume. The reverse transcription (RT) reaction was performed at 42 \u2022 C for 50 min. The cDNA was amplified in a 25 L reaction mixture containing 1 L cDNA, 12.5 L nanoPCR Mixture (GRED-BIO, Weihai, China), 0.5 L Taq DNA polymerase (GREDBIO, Weihai, China), and 10 M each of forward and reverse primer by following the manufacturer's protocol with the following cycling times and temperatures: 94 \u2022 C for 3 min and 30 cycles of 94 \u2022 C for 30 s, 55 \u2022 C for 30 s, and 72 \u2022 C for 25 s. Five microliters of nanoPCR products were analyzed by agarose gel electrophoresis. The size of PEDV fragments amplified by nanoPCR was 477 bp (Fig. 1) . Subsequent sequence analysis showed high similarity (100%) between the products obtained with the nanoPCR amplification of the N gene of PEDV (the objective sequences) and the reference sequence of PEDV. The results indicated that the PEDV nanoPCR method is specific.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 687,
                    "end": 695,
                    "text": "(Fig. 1)",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "section": "Fig. 1."
        },
        {
            "text": "To examine the sensitivity of the PEDV nanoPCR, RT-PCR and nanoPCR reaction were conducted using various concentrations of PEDV RNA as template. For this, the PEDV RNA was quantified by NanoDrop 1000 (Thermo Scientific, USA) and was diluted serially 10-fold from 2.7 to 2.7 \u00d7 10 \u22128 ng/L as template. The nanoPCR assay was performed using the optimized reaction parameters. The RT-PCR assay was performed using the same primers and reaction parameters as used for the nanoPCR. Briefly, the conventional RT-PCR assay for the detection of PEDV was performed in a 25-L reaction mixture containing 1 L cDNA, 12.5 L conventional PCR Mixture, 0.5 L Taq DNA polymerase, and 10 M each of the forward and the reverse primer. Five microliters of the nanoPCR and the RT-PCR products were analyzed by agarose gel electrophoresis. The detection limit of the nanoPCR was 2.7 \u00d7 10 \u22126 ng/L, whereas that of the RT-PCR was 2.7 \u00d7 10 \u22124 copies/L (Fig. 2) . Comparisons between the nanoPCR and the RT-PCR amplification indicated that the nanoPCR was 100-fold more sensitive than the RT-PCR assay ( Fig. 2A and B) .",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 926,
                    "end": 934,
                    "text": "(Fig. 2)",
                    "ref_id": null
